In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and hook into the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Created");
    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Activated");
    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Deactivated");
    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Stopped");
    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Resumed");
    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Destroying");
    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Backgrounding");

    return window;
}
```

**Typical transition order:**

| Scenario | Events |
|---|---|
| App launch | `Created → Activated` |
| Backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |
| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |
| iOS backgrounding | `Backgrounding` (save state via `BackgroundingEventArgs.State`) |

> **Note:** `Backgrounding` fires only on iOS/Mac Catalyst and gives you a `IPersistedState` dictionary to save transient data. On Android/Windows the equivalent save point is `Stopped`.
